158
00:09:14.264 --> 00:09:17.744
very few study investigate the long-lasting effects of

159
00:09:17.824 --> 00:09:20.284
smoking among the former smoker.

160
00:09:22.384 --> 00:09:25.764
So this research gap motivate us to conduct this study.

161
00:09:26.184 --> 00:09:30.164
We aim to develop a proteomic signature that reflects the

162
00:09:30.184 --> 00:09:34.024
persistent effects of the smoking, we call the PSPSE

163
00:09:34.184 --> 00:09:37.404
score, after quitting, and evaluate its

164
00:09:37.444 --> 00:09:40.704
association with the risk of smoking-related

165
00:09:40.784 --> 00:09:42.804
cancers among former smokers.

166
00:09:44.744 --> 00:09:46.524
So to address this research question,

167
00:09:47.704 --> 00:09:47.944
we

168
00:09:49.564 --> 00:09:53.064
analyzed over 37,000 UK Biobank

169
00:09:53.104 --> 00:09:56.684
participants who provide the proteomic data and

170
00:09:56.744 --> 00:10:00.624
certify the following exclusion criteria regarding the

171
00:10:00.644 --> 00:10:04.224
smoking history and the low missingness of the proteomic

172
00:10:04.264 --> 00:10:08.064
data. We further excluded the participants who had the cancer

173
00:10:08.124 --> 00:10:11.144
history or who developed the cancer during the follow-up time.

174
00:10:12.304 --> 00:10:14.024
And the final number of the participants

175
00:10:14.944 --> 00:10:17.884
included in our analysis was over

176
00:10:18.044 --> 00:10:19.504
28,000 participants.

177
00:10:20.744 --> 00:10:23.944
We divided these participants into the training and testing sets.

178
00:10:25.284 --> 00:10:28.664
So among the current and never smokers in the training sets,

179
00:10:29.324 --> 00:10:32.844
we conducted the linear regression analysis with its

180
00:10:32.864 --> 00:10:36.504
proteins at outcome and the smoking status as exposure.

181
00:10:37.484 --> 00:10:41.244
We found 1,725 proteins showing

182
00:10:41.304 --> 00:10:45.224
different levels between current and never smokers at the FDR

183
00:10:45.264 --> 00:10:46.744
level less than 0.05.

184
00:10:47.584 --> 00:10:51.304
And using this list of the proteins, we conduct the similar linear

185
00:10:51.364 --> 00:10:54.524
regression analysis among never and former smokers.

186
00:10:55.064 --> 00:10:56.044
And we identify

187
00:10:57.144 --> 00:11:01.004
627 proteins, showing different level between

188
00:11:01.064 --> 00:11:02.464
never and former smokers.

189
00:11:05.124 --> 00:11:08.564
And of these proteins, 177

190
00:11:08.574 --> 00:11:12.424
show persistently different levels between never and

191
00:11:12.464 --> 00:11:16.284
former smokers. And a protein is considered

192
00:11:16.294 --> 00:11:20.044
persistent if they show the different level across different

193
00:11:20.084 --> 00:11:24.044
quitting time windows, including less than 10 year, 10 to

194
00:11:24.144 --> 00:11:27.924
20 years, 20 to 30 years, and over 30 years.

195
00:11:29.444 --> 00:11:33.184
And interestingly, we found 41 proteins persistently

196
00:11:33.384 --> 00:11:37.324
change at least 10% in those who quit from 20 to

197
00:11:37.384 --> 00:11:40.884
30 years or over 30 years compared to never smoker.

198
00:11:41.884 --> 00:11:45.344
And to account for the multicollinearity, we conducted the lasso

199
00:11:45.404 --> 00:11:48.454
regression analysis. After tenfold

200
00:11:48.524 --> 00:11:52.174
cross-validation and 100 repeated times, we identified

201
00:11:52.304 --> 00:11:55.394
18 proteins and used it to develop the proteomic

202
00:11:55.564 --> 00:11:56.864
signature score.

203
00:11:58.304 --> 00:12:02.164
So this figure show us the distribution, the levels of the

204
00:12:02.204 --> 00:12:04.724
proteins included in our signature score.

205
00:12:04.884 --> 00:12:08.504
You can see that all the 18 proteins show in the different level

206
00:12:08.544 --> 00:12:12.304
between former and never smokers across different quitting time

207
00:12:12.344 --> 00:12:16.268
windows.And among the former smokers who quit from 20 to

208
00:12:16.348 --> 00:12:20.008
30 years or over 30 years, their levels

209
00:12:20.108 --> 00:12:21.728
saw at least a 10% change

210
00:12:22.568 --> 00:12:23.978
compared to never smokers.

211
00:12:26.168 --> 00:12:29.708
And the left-hand side figure here shows us the distribution of our signature

212
00:12:29.848 --> 00:12:33.808
score across smoking status. And you can see a clear gradient

213
00:12:33.948 --> 00:12:37.508
here that the current smokers have the highest score, former

214
00:12:37.568 --> 00:12:41.248
smokers were the middle, and never smokers had the lowest score.

215
00:12:42.128 --> 00:12:45.568
And our signature saw very similar discriminative

216
00:12:45.608 --> 00:12:49.358
performance to classify former and never smokers in

217
00:12:49.428 --> 00:12:51.328
either training and test sets.

218
00:12:54.728 --> 00:12:55.108
And

219
00:12:55.908 --> 00:12:59.828
our signature saw a very quick correlation with the years since quit

220
00:12:59.928 --> 00:13:03.908
smoking and moderate correlation with the smoking pack years

221
00:13:03.968 --> 00:13:06.828
among the former smokers, as you can see in these figures.

222
00:13:10.408 --> 00:13:14.308
Using the multivariable cost regression analysis, we found

223
00:13:14.328 --> 00:13:18.008
that our signature shows significant association with the different health

224
00:13:18.128 --> 00:13:21.208
