00:36:47.626 --> 00:36:51.386
that height PRS here represents the

621
00:36:51.406 --> 00:36:53.406
genetics of height very well.

622
00:36:55.986 --> 00:36:59.326
And if there's any other components of height

623
00:36:59.966 --> 00:37:03.606
that might be contributed by rarer variants

624
00:37:04.166 --> 00:37:04.906
and other

625
00:37:05.946 --> 00:37:09.216
genetic components that we cannot measure right now, but

626
00:37:09.286 --> 00:37:12.006
those might be, like I said,

627
00:37:13.146 --> 00:37:14.386
rarer. So

628
00:37:15.706 --> 00:37:18.026
as we see here, taller height,

629
00:37:19.906 --> 00:37:23.566
the association is more generalizable to our population.

630
00:37:23.586 --> 00:37:27.306
So I think those common variants may play a more important role

631
00:37:27.386 --> 00:37:27.626
here.

632
00:37:29.166 --> 00:37:30.046
Great. Thank you.

633
00:37:30.286 --> 00:37:30.646
Thank you.

634
00:37:31.246 --> 00:37:34.626
Our next speaker is Irma Wasak from

635
00:37:34.846 --> 00:37:35.386
Dartmouth.

636
00:37:48.666 --> 00:37:52.646
Hello, everyone. My name is Irma Wasak, and I'm a PhD candidate

637
00:37:52.706 --> 00:37:53.266
at Dartmouth.

638
00:37:54.806 --> 00:37:58.086
And I have no financial relationships to disclose.

639
00:37:59.886 --> 00:38:03.496
So high-grade serous ovarian carcinoma, or HSOC, is the most

640
00:38:04.406 --> 00:38:08.246
lethal subtype of ovarian cancer with a five-year survival rate of

641
00:38:08.426 --> 00:38:12.346
41%. This survival rate drops to less than 15%

642
00:38:12.446 --> 00:38:16.206
over 10 years. Unlike many other cancers, it's not

643
00:38:16.246 --> 00:38:20.086
driven by recurrent point mutations, but by widespread copy number

644
00:38:20.186 --> 00:38:21.966
alterations across the genome.

645
00:38:23.036 --> 00:38:26.386
This genomic instability shapes key features of the disease,

646
00:38:27.006 --> 00:38:30.926
including the tumor microenvironment, treatment response, and ultimately

647
00:38:30.966 --> 00:38:32.126
survival outcomes.

648
00:38:33.006 --> 00:38:36.776
So understanding patterns of copy number alteration is critical to

649
00:38:36.846 --> 00:38:40.726
understanding both tumor biology and clinical outcomes in

650
00:38:40.886 --> 00:38:41.626
HSOC.

651
00:38:43.506 --> 00:38:47.046
Over the past several decades, we've seen meaningful improvements in

652
00:38:47.186 --> 00:38:51.026
five-year survival for ovarian cancer, but those gains have not been shared

653
00:38:51.066 --> 00:38:54.536
equally. As you can see here, five-year survival has

654
00:38:54.566 --> 00:38:57.956
steadily increased among White women, reaching around

655
00:38:57.966 --> 00:39:01.826
50% in recent years. In contrast, survival

656
00:39:01.866 --> 00:39:05.666
among Black women has remained relatively flat, staying in the low

657
00:39:05.806 --> 00:39:06.706
40% range.

658
00:39:07.966 --> 00:39:11.496
So despite overall progress, these gains have not been shared equally,

659
00:39:12.006 --> 00:39:15.926
highlighting a persistent and widening disparity where one

660
00:39:15.986 --> 00:39:19.926
group benefits from advances in treatment and care, and another

661
00:39:19.946 --> 00:39:23.866
is largely left behind. This reinforces the need to better understand

662
00:39:23.926 --> 00:39:27.246
both biological and systemic factors contributing to these

663
00:39:27.266 --> 00:39:28.026
inequities.

664
00:39:29.686 --> 00:39:33.175
Building on these disparities, an important question is what's driving them?

665
00:39:33.846 --> 00:39:37.826
While differences in access to care and treatment certainly play a role,

666
00:39:37.835 --> 00:39:41.216
outcome disparities persist even after accounting for these factors,

667
00:39:41.706 --> 00:39:45.615
even among patients receiving guideline-concordant care, suggesting

668
00:39:45.666 --> 00:39:47.626
that this is not the full explanation.

669
00:39:48.366 --> 00:39:51.366
At the same time, our understanding of tumor biology and

670
00:39:51.586 --> 00:39:55.166
HSOC is based largely on cohorts of predominantly

671
00:39:55.246 --> 00:39:58.706
European ancestry, where race and ethnicity are often

672
00:39:58.726 --> 00:39:59.506
under-reported.

673
00:40:00.335 --> 00:40:03.946
This limits both generalizability and our ability to detect

674
00:40:04.146 --> 00:40:06.986
population-specific genomic patterns.

675
00:40:07.126 --> 00:40:10.426
Importantly, self-reported race is not a biological variable.

676
00:40:10.946 --> 00:40:14.556
It reflects social and structural exposures that shape health

677
00:40:14.686 --> 00:40:15.266
outcomes.

678
00:40:16.186 --> 00:40:19.946
So if we want to understand whether tumor biology differs, we need more

679
00:40:19.986 --> 00:40:23.946
precise ways to capture genetic ancestry and integrate that into our

680
00:40:24.006 --> 00:40:24.746
analyses.

681
00:40:25.566 --> 00:40:29.066
Given the high mortality of HSOC and its limited

682
00:40:29.146 --> 00:40:32.206
molecular stratification, this becomes especially

683
00:40:32.246 --> 00:40:36.146
important. In this study, we take an initial step toward that goal

684
00:40:36.266 --> 00:40:40.006
by focusing on tumor genomics, specifically characterizing

685
00:40:40.086 --> 00:40:43.556
copy number alteration-based clusters and evaluating their

686
00:40:43.586 --> 00:40:45.086
associations with survival.

687
00:40:46.906 --> 00:40:50.726
Our study includes 638 patients with high-grade serous ovarian

688
00:40:50.766 --> 00:40:53.606
carcinoma drawn from three large studies.

689
00:40:54.085 --> 00:40:57.666
The African American Cancer Epidemiology Study, or ACES, which is a

690
00:40:57.706 --> 00:41:01.626
population-based case control study focused on ovarian cancer disparities in

691
00:41:01.686 --> 00:41:05.626
African American women. The North Carolina Ovarian Cancer study, or

692
00:41:05.666 --> 00:41:08.826
NCSCS, is a multi-phase population-based case control

693
00:41:08.986 --> 00:41:12.906
study focused on epithelial ovarian cancer in residents of

694
00:41:12.946 --> 00:41:16.526
North Carolina. And the Nurses' Health Study one and two is a

695
00:41:16.546 --> 00:41:19.496
prospective cohort study of female registered nurses.

696
00:41:20.246 --> 00:41:24.035
Importantly, our cohort is relatively diverse, with about

697
00:41:24.186 --> 00:41:27.926
37% self-identifying as Black and 63% as

698
00:41:28.026 --> 00:41:28.286
White.

699
00:41:29.166 --> 00:41:32.806
Across groups, our clinical characteristics of our cohort

700
00:41:33.066 --> 00:41:36.846
are broadly similar, including age at diagnosis and stage distribution,

701
00:41:37.386 --> 00:41:40.326
with the majority of patients presenting with stage three disease.

702
00:41:40.926 --> 00:41:44.906
This provides a well-powered and clinically comparable cohort to evaluate

703
00:41:44.916 --> 00:41:48.636
patterns in copy number alterations and their association with

704
00:41:48.666 --> 00:41:51.766
survival. So we analyzed

705
00:41:52.306 --> 00:41:56.186
638 HSOC tumor samples with matched blood available for a

706
00:41:56.226 --> 00:41:59.386
subset of 296 patients that served as a reference.

707
00:42:00.166 --> 00:42:03.926
DNA was extracted from these samples and profiled using Illumina Epic

708
00:42:03.966 --> 00:42:07.686
methylation arrays. From these data, we infer genome-wide

709
00:42:07.746 --> 00:42:11.106
copy number alterations. We then use these CNA

710
00:42:11.126 --> 00:42:14.506
profiles to perform unsupervised clustering and evaluated

711
00:42:14.566 --> 00:42:16.586
associations with overall survival.

712
00:42:17.426 --> 00:42:21.286
In parallel, we integrated self-reported race to assess differences in

713
00:42:21.326 --> 00:42:23.066
CNA patterns across groups.

714
00:42:25.866 --> 00:42:29.646
Here, we cluster tumors based on genome-wide copy number profiles,

715
00:42:30.066 --> 00:42:32.726
which revealed three distinct copy number alteration

716
00:42:32.786 --> 00:42:36.226
profiles.Starting with cluster one, which

717
00:42:36.266 --> 00:42:40.056
comprises 43.7% of the overall cohort, this

718
00:42:40.086 --> 00:42:43.666
group is dominated by widespread copy number loss across the

719
00:42:43.706 --> 00:42:46.966
genome, resulting in a high fraction of the genome altered,

720
00:42:47.366 --> 00:42:49.346
primarily driven by deletions.

721
00:42:51.706 --> 00:42:55.366
Cluster two represents 39.7% of the overall cohort,

722
00:42:55.886 --> 00:42:59.856
and this cluster is relatively CNA quiet, with most of

723
00:42:59.886 --> 00:43:02.366
the genome remaining copy number neutral.

724
00:43:03.886 --> 00:43:07.866
And lastly, cluster three, which comprises 16.6%

725
00:43:07.906 --> 00:43:11.686
of the overall cohort, shows widespread copy number gains across

726
00:43:11.746 --> 00:43:12.735
many chromosomes.

727
00:43:14.366 --> 00:43:18.086
Together, these clusters defined three major

728
00:43:18.246 --> 00:43:21.766
copy number alteration subtypes: loss dominant, CNA

729
00:43:21.866 --> 00:43:23.706
quiet, and gain dominant tumors.

730
00:43:24.526 --> 00:43:28.026
These patterns are clearly reflected in this heat map, with widespread

731
00:43:28.066 --> 00:43:31.826
deletions in cluster one and broad amplifications in

732
00:43:31.866 --> 00:43:35.426
cluster three, while cluster two remains relatively stable.

733
00:43:36.386 --> 00:43:39.806
We also recapitulate known features of HSOC

734
00:43:39.886 --> 00:43:43.506
biology. For example, the Myc region shows recurrent

735
00:43:43.586 --> 00:43:46.896
amplification, particularly in the gain dominant cluster.

736
00:43:47.726 --> 00:43:51.506
But importantly, our goal is not to just recover known events like Myc

737
00:43:51.626 --> 00:43:55.566
amplification. By defining these clusters, we can start to place these

738
00:43:55.626 --> 00:43:59.566
alterations in a broader genomic context and ask whether these

739
00:43:59.646 --> 00:44:03.166
specific gains and losses are differentially enriched across

740
00:44:03.186 --> 00:44:07.106
subtypes. This allows us to move beyond single events

741
00:44:07.246 --> 00:44:10.686
and begin identifying cluster-specific patterns that may

742
00:44:10.766 --> 00:44:13.366
reflect distinct underlying biology.

743
00:44:15.046 --> 00:44:18.646
Next, we evaluated overall survival across the CNA-based

744
00:44:18.706 --> 00:44:22.246
clusters using the CNA quiet group, C2, as a

745
00:44:22.286 --> 00:44:25.746
reference. While the unadjusted Kaplan-Meier curves are not

746
00:44:25.806 --> 00:44:28.726
statistically significant, the adjusted Cox model

747
00:44:28.826 --> 00:44:32.806
reveals a clearer pattern. Both the loss dominant

748
00:44:32.846 --> 00:44:36.666
cluster, C1, and the gain dominant cluster, C3, are

749
00:44:36.676 --> 00:44:40.356
associated with a higher hazard of death compared to C2, with

750
00:44:40.386 --> 00:44:44.266
C1 reaching statistical significance.

751
00:44:45.106 --> 00:44:48.746
These results are adjusted for key clinical factors, including age,

752
00:44:49.046 --> 00:44:51.446
stage, study, and epithelial proportion.

753
00:44:52.306 --> 00:44:56.046
Overall, this suggests that CNA quiet tumors are associated

754
00:44:56.086 --> 00:44:58.106
with improved survival outcomes.

755
00:44:59.266 --> 00:45:03.066
Next, we asked whether the CNA subtypes might help explain survival

756
00:45:03.106 --> 00:45:07.046
disparities by race. Importantly, cluster membership itself did

757
00:45:07.086 --> 00:45:10.946
not differ by race. However, within the gain dominant cluster,

758
00:45:11.106 --> 00:45:12.906
we observe a significant difference.

759
00:45:13.386 --> 00:45:17.026
Black patients have higher hazard of death compared to white patients after

760
00:45:17.146 --> 00:45:21.126
adjustment. This difference is not observed in the loss dominant or

761
00:45:21.206 --> 00:45:25.166
CNA quiet clusters. Overall, this suggests that disparities

762
00:45:25.186 --> 00:45:28.646
in survival may be concentrated within specific tumor

763
00:45:28.706 --> 00:45:32.606
subtypes rather than uniform across all HSOC.

764
00:45:34.606 --> 00:45:38.376
To better understand the biology underlying these CNA-defined clusters,

765
00:45:38.746 --> 00:45:40.596
we next looked at tumor composition.

766
00:45:41.346 --> 00:45:45.226
Using the same DNA methylation data, we applied HYTIME to deconvolve each

767
00:45:45.266 --> 00:45:49.166
tumor into immune, stromal, endothelial, and epithelial components.

768
00:45:49.866 --> 00:45:53.606
For our downstream analyses, we focus on the epithelial-like fraction,

769
00:45:53.946 --> 00:45:57.265
which captures both tumor and epithelial cells.

770
00:45:57.735 --> 00:46:01.646
This allows us to begin linking the CNA patterns we identified to

771
00:46:01.686 --> 00:46:05.326
differences in underlying tumor biology.

772
00:46:05.426 --> 00:46:09.396
Using the HYTIME deconvolution, we next examined how tumor composition

773
00:46:09.426 --> 00:46:12.676
varies across CNA subtypes. While there is

774
00:46:12.706 --> 00:46:16.646
heterogeneity across tumors, a clear pattern emerges when we

775
00:46:16.686 --> 00:46:17.706
look by cluster.

776
00:46:19.466 --> 00:46:22.766
The CNA quiet group shows significantly higher levels of immune

777
00:46:22.806 --> 00:46:26.406
infiltration, including mononuclear cells, B cells,

778
00:46:26.846 --> 00:46:30.386
natural killer cells, and T cells compared to both the

779
00:46:30.406 --> 00:46:34.396
loss and gain dominant clusters. In contrast, the other

780
00:46:34.406 --> 00:46:37.786
clusters tend to have lower immune infiltration overall.

781
00:46:37.826 --> 00:46:41.226
This suggests that the CNA quiet subtype is characterized by a more

782
00:46:41.266 --> 00:46:44.546
immune-enriched microenvironment, which may help explain its

783
00:46:44.586 --> 00:46:46.966
association with better overall survival.

784
00:46:49.446 --> 00:46:52.706
In summary, we identified three CNA-defined subtypes of

785
00:46:52.865 --> 00:46:56.726
HSOC that capture substantial genomic heterogeneity.

786
00:46:57.306 --> 00:47:00.406
These subtypes are clinically and biologically meaningful.

787
00:47:00.886 --> 00:47:04.756
CNA quiet tumors show increased immune infiltration and improved survival,

788
00:47:05.186 --> 00:47:08.886
while loss and gain dominant tumors are associated with worse outcomes.

789
00:47:09.686 --> 00:47:13.586
Importantly, when we look within subtypes, we find that survival disparities

790
00:47:13.606 --> 00:47:16.986
by race are concentrated in the gain dominant cluster

791
00:47:17.406 --> 00:47:19.666
rather than uniform across all tumors.

792
00:47:21.206 --> 00:47:24.906
Moving forward, we are extending this work by incorporating local

793
00:47:25.046 --> 00:47:28.586
ancestry to better identify ancestry-specific genomic

794
00:47:28.646 --> 00:47:32.406
patterns and by investigating how CNA landscapes shape the

795
00:47:32.446 --> 00:47:36.106
tumor immune microenvironment. Ultimately, this may help

796
00:47:36.226 --> 00:47:39.806
inform more biologically grounded and equitable

797
00:47:39.886 --> 00:47:42.546
approaches to risk stratification and treatment.

798
00:47:44.166 --> 00:47:47.786
With that, I'd like to say thank you, especially to the ACES, NHS, and NCO

799
00:47:47.866 --> 00:47:51.706
CS, and the patients who made this research possible, and thank you to all of my

800
00:47:51.746 --> 00:47:55.306
co-authors and everyone here for taking the time to attend this talk.

801
00:47:55.326 --> 00:47:58.226
With that, I'm happy to take any questions. Thank you.

802
00:48:02.646 --> 00:48:04.426
Thank you very much. Very exciting research.

803
00:48:04.506 --> 00:48:05.246
Thank you.

804
00:48:05.306 --> 00:48:05.746
Questions?

805
00:48:07.866 --> 00:48:11.586
Yes. Nice work. I'm wondering with all of the

806
00:48:11.646 --> 00:48:14.926
