We observed that Wnt mutated DTC positive tumors had an

1278
01:16:51.210 --> 01:16:54.990
increase in epithelial mesenchymal transition signaling.

1279
01:16:55.370 --> 01:16:59.030
And this pathway is important in which could lead to

1280
01:16:59.050 --> 01:17:02.850
migration, invasion, and increased survival at distant sites.

1281
01:17:06.890 --> 01:17:10.750
Conversely, these tumors also showed downregulation of proliferative pathways,

1282
01:17:10.850 --> 01:17:14.690
and taken together, these findings suggest that Wnt mutations in

1283
01:17:14.730 --> 01:17:18.630
DTC positive tumors are shifting the transcriptional state of the

1284
01:17:18.830 --> 01:17:22.210
tumor away from proliferation and towards a dedifferentiated

1285
01:17:22.270 --> 01:17:23.550
mesenchymal-like program.

1286
01:17:29.930 --> 01:17:33.530
In contrast, PI3 kinase mutated tumors showed broad

1287
01:17:33.540 --> 01:17:36.330
transcriptional upregulation of proliferative pathways.

1288
01:17:36.930 --> 01:17:40.870
The one exception to upregulation of downstream pathways was

1289
01:17:40.910 --> 01:17:41.890
apoptosis.

1290
01:17:43.710 --> 01:17:46.950
And this suggests that these tumors are increasing

1291
01:17:46.990 --> 01:17:50.590
proliferation without regulating cell death.

1292
01:17:52.810 --> 01:17:56.590
And importantly, in our cohort, we observed that this was independent of estrogen

1293
01:17:56.650 --> 01:18:00.640
receptor signaling, which could indicate that these patients have

1294
01:18:00.670 --> 01:18:03.390
an increased propensity for endocrine therapy resistance.

1295
01:18:06.950 --> 01:18:10.380
So in summary, we observed that in our cohort, breast cancer patients with

1296
01:18:10.390 --> 01:18:13.510
disseminated tumor cells in the bone marrow at the time of diagnosis

1297
01:18:14.350 --> 01:18:17.970
were characterized not by single driver genes, but rather

1298
01:18:18.010 --> 01:18:20.210
by somatic mutations in

1299
01:18:21.030 --> 01:18:24.610
major breast cancer pathways, including Wnt, PI3 kinase,

1300
01:18:25.270 --> 01:18:26.110
and NRF2.

1301
01:18:28.670 --> 01:18:32.570
We observed that for DTC positive patients with somatic mutations in the

1302
01:18:32.590 --> 01:18:33.300
Wnt pathway,

1303
01:18:35.090 --> 01:18:38.720
had an increase in epithelial mesenchymal transition signaling,

1304
01:18:39.570 --> 01:18:43.350
and a decrease in proliferative signaling, which is consistent with a stem-like

1305
01:18:43.390 --> 01:18:47.170
migratory phenotype that might be primed for dissemination and survival in the bone

1306
01:18:47.230 --> 01:18:47.470
marrow.

1307
01:18:49.710 --> 01:18:51.480
For somatic mutations in the

1308
01:18:51.550 --> 01:18:54.950
PI3/AKT/mTOR pathway, we observed that

1309
01:18:55.470 --> 01:18:57.150
these were associated with an increase in

1310
01:18:58.070 --> 01:18:59.470
proliferative pathway expression,

1311
01:19:00.830 --> 01:19:02.590
and a decrease in apoptosis.

1312
01:19:04.670 --> 01:19:07.510
We also observed increased APOBEC mutagenesis.

1313
01:19:09.950 --> 01:19:13.910
And this suggests that there's really likely multiple interrelated pathways that

1314
01:19:13.950 --> 01:19:17.690
are driving dissemination. It's going to depend on the timing of dissemination as

1315
01:19:17.750 --> 01:19:20.810
well as the specific subtype that we're looking at.

1316
01:19:21.130 --> 01:19:24.930
But these preliminary results may suggest that APOBEC mutagenesis,

1317
01:19:25.430 --> 01:19:26.850
Wnt pathway mutations,

1318
01:19:27.690 --> 01:19:31.550
PI3 kinase pathway mutations, as well as NRF2

1319
01:19:31.990 --> 01:19:34.650
may be potential biomarkers for high-risk patients.

1320
01:19:35.890 --> 01:19:38.990
This is largely hypothesis-generating given our limited sample

1321
01:19:39.050 --> 01:19:43.002
size.And now I'm going to briefly talk about next steps

1322
01:19:43.022 --> 01:19:46.992
and future directions. So these were results from preliminary

1323
01:19:47.062 --> 01:19:50.802
analyses. We're continuing sequencing efforts to increase our sample

1324
01:19:50.882 --> 01:19:53.422
size to 700 by the end of 2026.

1325
01:19:55.582 --> 01:19:59.322
We're evaluating the functional relevance of pathways with decreased

1326
01:19:59.362 --> 01:20:03.082
mutational burden to see if these pathways may be driven by

1327
01:20:03.122 --> 01:20:05.502
cell-intrinsic factors or the tumor immune

1328
01:20:05.562 --> 01:20:09.312
microenvironment. We're also using

1329
01:20:09.342 --> 01:20:13.082
single-cell deconvolution and spatial transcriptomics to distinguish tumor

1330
01:20:13.122 --> 01:20:16.422
intrinsic from tumor microenvironmental and extrinsic factors.

1331
01:20:18.142 --> 01:20:21.522
We're currently building TMAs for

1332
01:20:21.942 --> 01:20:24.902
validation of some of the markers and the pathways identified today.

1333
01:20:26.662 --> 01:20:27.882
And then ultimately, since the

1334
01:20:31.322 --> 01:20:35.232
clinical relevance of these findings really depends on not only if

1335
01:20:35.622 --> 01:20:39.542
these molecular features are associated with the presence of disseminated

1336
01:20:39.562 --> 01:20:43.372
tumor cells at the time of diagnosis, but if they're also associated with

1337
01:20:43.402 --> 01:20:47.002
distant recurrence. And so this is an actively recruiting cohort.

1338
01:20:47.042 --> 01:20:50.462
We won't have long-term follow-up for a lot of these ER-positive breast cancer

1339
01:20:50.542 --> 01:20:53.922
patients. We may not observe recurrence for a lot of these

1340
01:20:53.982 --> 01:20:57.722
ER-positive breast cancer patients until 10 to 15 to 20 years.

1341
01:20:58.422 --> 01:21:02.382
So we're going to be leveraging a complementary cohort, which has molecular

1342
01:21:02.442 --> 01:21:06.062
data that was sequenced in the same lab and has

1343
01:21:06.102 --> 01:21:10.062
long-term follow-up data through EHR linkages up to 15 years

1344
01:21:10.142 --> 01:21:11.262
after diagnosis.

1345
01:21:12.642 --> 01:21:15.512
I just want to say a huge thank you to my primary mentor, Dr.

1346
01:21:15.742 --> 01:21:18.482
Chris Lee, and everybody involved in our research team.

1347
01:21:19.002 --> 01:21:22.862
The Gehar Lab at Fred Hutch does all of the single-cell sequencing for our DTCs,

1348
01:21:22.922 --> 01:21:24.182
and it's an immense amount of work.

1349
01:21:24.602 --> 01:21:27.942
So I just want to recognize everybody involved, and I'm not going to end with

1350
01:21:28.002 --> 01:21:31.602
questions quite yet. I just want to share an advocate

1351
01:21:31.662 --> 01:21:35.342
perspective. As part of our study, we work really closely with patient advocates,

1352
01:21:35.402 --> 01:21:38.562
and one of the patient advocates, Debbie, who we worked with,

1353
01:21:39.582 --> 01:21:42.302
provided some thoughts on these results.

1354
01:21:42.342 --> 01:21:44.222
And what she really emphasized was that

1355
01:21:45.422 --> 01:21:48.882
it's really important to ensure cancers with high risk of recurrence receive

1356
01:21:48.922 --> 01:21:50.922
appropriate therapy, but also

1357
01:21:51.882 --> 01:21:55.562
important to ensure that we're sparing patients with lower risk cancers, the

1358
01:21:55.602 --> 01:21:58.722
toxicities of treatment that they would offer no additional benefit.

1359
01:21:59.082 --> 01:22:01.362
That's really where risk stratification comes into play.

1360
01:22:02.662 --> 01:22:05.101
And then I'll open up for questions with whatever time we have left.

1361
01:22:05.522 --> 01:22:07.162
Sorry about the technical difficulties.

1362
01:22:11.302 --> 01:22:13.262
Yes, thanks very much. Very cool and unique study.

1363
01:22:14.402 --> 01:22:16.362
I think we have time for one question.

1364
01:22:25.242 --> 01:22:27.162
Hi. Sabina Kasimbauer from Germany.

1365
01:22:27.242 --> 01:22:31.182
We're also working on DTCs, and my question is, how do you detect the cells

1366
01:22:31.222 --> 01:22:31.812
and how many

1367
01:22:32.902 --> 01:22:36.202
bone marrow cells do you evaluate to detect these cells?

1368
01:22:36.262 --> 01:22:37.802
And when is a patient positive?

1369
01:22:38.562 --> 01:22:41.702
Yeah, that's a great question. So that's being performed by the Gehar Lab, and

1370
01:22:41.722 --> 01:22:43.652
they're using single-cell sequencing.

1371
01:22:44.622 --> 01:22:46.392
So they take the bone marrow aspirate,

1372
01:22:47.502 --> 01:22:49.042
and they have a

1373
01:22:50.142 --> 01:22:51.542
single-cell sequencing technique.

1374
01:22:51.602 --> 01:22:53.582
I'm not as familiar with the actual technical

1375
01:22:55.022 --> 01:22:58.082
aspects of it, but I have the paper that I can send to you as a reference.

1376
01:22:58.422 --> 01:23:02.322
But essentially, one of the first steps is detecting things like EpCAM

1377
01:23:02.332 --> 01:23:06.202
markers. Well, actually, the first step, I think, is removing a lot of the

1378
01:23:06.242 --> 01:23:09.222
fat and tissue that they don't want from the bone marrow aspirate.

1379
01:23:09.282 --> 01:23:09.962
Then after that,

1380
01:23:11.082 --> 01:23:14.642
to actually detect the DTCs amongst all of the other

1381
01:23:14.962 --> 01:23:17.302
osteocytes and other cells that you would find in the bone marrow.

1382
01:23:17.862 --> 01:23:20.262
The first marker that they're using is EpCAM.

1383
01:23:21.142 --> 01:23:22.212
After that, this

1384
01:23:23.162 --> 01:23:26.602
is something they've been working on for the last three years and adjusting over

1385
01:23:26.702 --> 01:23:30.042
time to identify other markers of DTCs.

1386
01:23:32.102 --> 01:23:32.502
And

1387
01:23:34.482 --> 01:23:36.282
I can send you the paper that has more-

1388
01:23:36.362 --> 01:23:36.792
Yeah, that would be great.

1389
01:23:36.792 --> 01:23:38.042
-technical information on it. Yeah.

1390
01:23:38.102 --> 01:23:38.982
Okay. Thank you.

1391
01:23:39.042 --> 01:23:39.162
Yep.

1392
01:23:44.242 --> 01:23:47.182
I'd like to invite our next speaker, Xinyu

1393
01:23:47.222 --> 01:23:48.242
Wang.

1394
01:23:52.942 --> 01:23:55.362
So good afternoon, everyone. I'm Xinyu Wang.

1395
01:23:55.482 --> 01:23:59.342
I'm a master's student from Department of Epidemiology, Harvard Chan School of

1396
01:23:59.362 --> 01:24:03.061
Public Health. It's my great honor to be here today to present our

1397
01:24:03.101 --> 01:24:06.922
project titled "Germline Genetic Impact on Risk of Colorectal

1398
01:24:07.022 --> 01:24:08.722
Cancer According to Birth Cohort."

1399
01:24:09.962 --> 01:24:12.942
First of all, I have no financial relationships to disclose.

1400
01:24:14.222 --> 01:24:17.962
Colorectal cancer is the third most commonly diagnosed cancer and the

1401
01:24:18.002 --> 01:24:21.002
second leading cause of cancer-related deaths worldwide.

1402
01:24:21.502 --> 01:24:25.222
Over the past few decades, there have been distinct trends in CRC

1403
01:24:25.232 --> 01:24:28.942
incidence according to age. In contrast to a slight

1404
01:24:28.982 --> 01:24:32.882
decrease among people aged 50 years or above, there is

1405
01:24:33.022 --> 01:24:36.382
a rapid increasing trend for early-onset CRC.

1406
01:24:37.042 --> 01:24:40.822
Although the underlying cause of early-onset CRC remain largely unclear,

1407
01:24:41.242 --> 01:24:45.162
birth cohort effect is believed to play a very important role, given

1408
01:24:45.182 --> 01:24:48.822
the observation that the increasing trend of CRC

1409
01:24:48.882 --> 01:24:52.062
incidence is primarily observed among people born after

1410
01:24:52.162 --> 01:24:56.042
1950s or 1960s. Individuals born in more

1411
01:24:56.082 --> 01:24:59.922
recent birth cohorts have a very different exposure history

1412
01:24:59.962 --> 01:25:03.892
compared to those born in the earlier cohorts, characterized by

1413
01:25:03.962 --> 01:25:07.412
an epidemic of obesity, particularly childhood obesity,

1414
01:25:07.782 --> 01:25:11.342
increasing prevalence of sedentary behavior and ultra-processed food

1415
01:25:11.402 --> 01:25:15.282
intake, as well as higher pollution and environmental chemicals.

1416
01:25:15.752 --> 01:25:19.402
So this suggests that birth cohort may serve as a broad,

1417
01:25:19.502 --> 01:25:23.162
great proxy for us to capture composite and cumulative

1418
01:25:23.222 --> 01:25:26.846
lifetime exposure history.In addition to

1419
01:25:26.866 --> 01:25:30.446
environmental risk factors, genetic factors are also playing very

1420
01:25:30.466 --> 01:25:34.426
important roles in colorectal carcinogenesis, and the genetic

1421
01:25:34.466 --> 01:25:38.206
effects might be modified by environmental exposure, together

1422
01:25:38.246 --> 01:25:41.826
forming the notion of gene environmental interaction in colorectal

1423
01:25:41.886 --> 01:25:45.746
cancer. A previous study reported that a polygenic risk

1424
01:25:45.806 --> 01:25:49.486
score of CRC was more strongly associated with early

1425
01:25:49.526 --> 01:25:53.226
onset compared to late onset CRC. However, simply

1426
01:25:53.266 --> 01:25:57.106
stratifying by age at diagnosis may not be adequate to

1427
01:25:57.166 --> 01:26:00.346
capture the underlying biology of early onset CRC,

1428
01:26:00.926 --> 01:26:04.826
since individuals diagnosed at the same age may come from

1429
01:26:04.886 --> 01:26:08.706
different birth cohorts and may therefore have been exposed to

1430
01:26:08.906 --> 01:26:11.086
very different environmental risk factors.

1431
01:26:11.646 --> 01:26:15.515
Therefore, we aimed to further examine the association between

1432
01:26:15.526 --> 01:26:19.406
PRS and CRC across different birth cohorts, and we

1433
01:26:19.506 --> 01:26:23.466
specifically hypothesized that the CRC PRS

1434
01:26:23.506 --> 01:26:27.146
is more strongly associated with colorectal cancer risk in the more

1435
01:26:27.186 --> 01:26:31.126
recent than remote birth cohort, reflecting the interaction

1436
01:26:31.226 --> 01:26:34.906
between genetic susceptibility and the changing environmental

1437
01:26:34.966 --> 01:26:35.666
landscapes.

1438
01:26:37.306 --> 01:26:40.426
So the current study used data from two main sources.

1439
01:26:40.546 --> 01:26:44.506
One is Genetics and Epidemiology of Colorectal Cancer Consortium,

1440
01:26:44.886 --> 01:26:48.606
GEcco, which is a large international collaboration that

1441
01:26:48.666 --> 01:26:52.166
included well-characterized case control studies and cohort

1442
01:26:52.246 --> 01:26:55.286
studies conducted in North America and Europe.

1443
01:26:55.746 --> 01:26:59.126
The other is UK Biobank, which is a well-known large

1444
01:26:59.366 --> 01:27:03.346
prospective cohort study. And by putting these two studies together,

1445
01:27:03.486 --> 01:27:07.366
we managed to get more than 31,000 cases and more than

1446
01:27:07.546 --> 01:27:11.466
52,000 controls. And down below, we show the

1447
01:27:11.506 --> 01:27:15.386
distribution of our participants across different birth cohorts, and we

1448
01:27:15.446 --> 01:27:18.826
can see that most of our participants are born between

1449
01:27:18.866 --> 01:27:20.486
1920 to 1960.

1450
01:27:22.126 --> 01:27:25.966
For statistical analysis, we calculated the polygenic

1451
01:27:26.046 --> 01:27:29.986
risk score of CRC by the weighted sum of risk alleles

1452
01:27:30.026 --> 01:27:33.906
across 204 autosomal genetic variants reported by the

1453
01:27:33.965 --> 01:27:37.926
most recent and the largest CRC GWAS, which together

1454
01:27:37.986 --> 01:27:41.526
explained nearly 20% of familiar risk of

1455
01:27:41.586 --> 01:27:44.886
CRC. We used logistical regression to assess the

1456
01:27:44.966 --> 01:27:48.686
association between PRS and CRC by birth cohort,

1457
01:27:49.086 --> 01:27:52.996
adjusted for sex, genotyping platform, study, and top 10

1458
01:27:52.996 --> 01:27:56.566
genetic principal components to account for population stratification.

1459
01:27:57.206 --> 01:28:00.746
All the analysis were conducted in GEcco and UK Biobank

1460
01:28:00.826 --> 01:28:04.726
separately, and we meta-analyzed the results using fixed effects

1461
01:28:04.806 --> 01:28:08.646
models. To assess whether the birth cohort effect of

1462
01:28:08.686 --> 01:28:12.526
PRS differ by subgroups, we further performed the subgroup

1463
01:28:12.546 --> 01:28:16.186
analysis by age at diagnosis, history of screening,

1464
01:28:16.306 --> 01:28:19.915
family history of CRC, as well as CRC subsites and

1465
01:28:20.006 --> 01:28:23.866
molecular features. To better understand the underlying

1466
01:28:23.926 --> 01:28:27.526
mechanisms, we performed a pathway analysis by first

1467
01:28:27.606 --> 01:28:31.406
examining the interaction between individual SNPs

1468
01:28:31.446 --> 01:28:35.386
comprising the CRC PRS and birth year in relation to

1469
01:28:35.426 --> 01:28:39.066
CRC. We performed a downstream functional annotation and

1470
01:28:39.166 --> 01:28:42.486
conducted a gene set enrichment analysis, as well as

1471
01:28:42.546 --> 01:28:46.366
overrepresentation analysis to assess whether the genetic

1472
01:28:46.446 --> 01:28:50.386
variants that show a stronger birth cohort are enriched in

1473
01:28:50.446 --> 01:28:52.276
specific biological pathways.

1474
01:28:53.496 --> 01:28:56.246
So here is the overview of our study results.

1475
01:28:56.766 --> 01:29:00.535
In Panel A, we show that the distribution of PRS did not

1476
01:29:00.566 --> 01:29:03.106
differ significantly by birth cohort.

1477
01:29:03.566 --> 01:29:07.126
So this suggests that the prevalence of genetic risk factors

1478
01:29:07.166 --> 01:29:10.866
itself did not change significantly across

1479
01:29:10.906 --> 01:29:14.826
generations. In Panel B, we show that the association

1480
01:29:14.886 --> 01:29:18.726
between PRS and CRC is generally increasing in more recent

1481
01:29:18.806 --> 01:29:22.486
birth cohorts compared to earlier ones, with a P value for

1482
01:29:22.546 --> 01:29:24.486
trend less than 0.001.

1483
01:29:26.126 --> 01:29:29.986
When we examine the association by subgroups, first

1484
01:29:30.086 --> 01:29:33.846
by age at diagnosis, we primarily observe the birth cohort

1485
01:29:33.946 --> 01:29:37.626
effect of PRS among those younger than 55

1486
01:29:37.666 --> 01:29:40.846
years old, as indicated by the red line here.

1487
01:29:41.126 --> 01:29:44.606
In contrast, the magnitude of association is slightly

1488
01:29:44.626 --> 01:29:48.366
decreasing among people older than 75 years old, as

1489
01:29:48.426 --> 01:29:52.056
indicated by the green line here. And in Panel B, by

1490
01:29:52.106 --> 01:29:55.496
history of screening, we consistently observed a stronger

1491
01:29:55.546 --> 01:29:59.146
association between PRS and CRC among unscreened

1492
01:29:59.246 --> 01:30:01.446
individuals compared to screened ones.

1493
01:30:01.986 --> 01:30:05.526
Consistently, we primarily observed the birth cohort effect of

1494
01:30:05.586 --> 01:30:08.346
CRC among those without a family history

1495
01:30:08.406 --> 01:30:12.366
of CRC, as indicated by the

1496
01:30:12.386 --> 01:30:16.106
blue line here, which may also due to the effect of screening,

1497
01:30:16.246 --> 01:30:20.226
since participants with a family history of CRC tend

1498
01:30:20.266 --> 01:30:23.196
to engage more in screening practices.

1499
01:30:23.606 --> 01:30:26.916
And again, the association between PRS and CRC is

1500
01:30:26.966 --> 01:30:30.806
attenuated among screened individuals.

1501
01:30:31.046 --> 01:30:34.506
And when we assess the CRC subtypes,

1502
01:30:35.106 --> 01:30:39.086
we primarily observe the birth cohort effect of PRS for distal

1503
01:30:39.126 --> 01:30:42.906
colon cancers and rectal cancers compared

1504
01:30:42.986 --> 01:30:46.806
to proximal colon cancers. This is also consistent

1505
01:30:46.946 --> 01:30:50.746
with the observation that the rising incidence of early onset CRC

1506
01:30:51.146 --> 01:30:54.626
is primarily observed for these two cancer sites rather than

1507
01:30:54.666 --> 01:30:58.166
proximal colon cancers. And we did not observe

1508
01:30:58.266 --> 01:31:02.076
significant birth cohort trend by molecular subtypes,

1509
01:31:02.426 --> 01:31:05.586
but only around 20% of CRC cases in our

1510
01:31:06.046 --> 01:31:09.966
study have molecular data, which might limit our statistical

1511
01:31:10.026 --> 01:31:10.406
power.

1512
01:31:11.866 --> 01:31:15.766
In gene set enrichment analysis, we identify the innate immune

1513
01:31:15.826 --> 01:31:19.246
system as the top enriched pathway, which might

1514
01:31:19.586 --> 01:31:23.426
explain the underlying mechanism of the birth cohort effect

1515
01:31:23.486 --> 01:31:26.946
of PRS in relation to CRC. And we also

1516
01:31:27.326 --> 01:31:30.026
get very similar results using overrepresentation

1517
01:31:30.086 --> 01:31:33.922
analysis.The strength of the current study

1518
01:31:33.962 --> 01:31:37.572
includes the large sample size, which enable us to detail the

1519
01:31:37.582 --> 01:31:41.542
evaluated PRS associated CRC risk across different

1520
01:31:41.562 --> 01:31:45.482
birth cohorts, both overall and within the subgroups.

1521
01:31:45.962 --> 01:31:49.772
And we did centralized harmonization of phenotype and genotype

